727732f-b.text:
Queens Boulevard, south side, between Fifty-forth and Fifty-fifth Avenues, showing in three views the First Presbyterian Church of Newtown. Views one and two show the front and rear of the the edifice. John Goldsmith Payntor who died in 1891 left the parish sufficient money for the erection of the store structure. The cornerstone was laid July 6, 1893 and the edifice was dedicated hay 5, 1895. View No. 3 is taken from a point south of Justice Avenue, between Fifty-fifth and Fifty-second Avenues, viewing south and shows in the foreground the old Church and cemetery on the north side of the Boulevard between Fifty-fifth Avenue and Broadway.
1922
Views 2&3: May 1923
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

727731f-d.text:
Queens Boulevard, at the S.E. corner of 54th Ave, showing the Presbyterian First Church of Newtown, erected 1893, which replaced the old wooden edifice across the street (view 3, right).

Views 2,3 and 4 show the granite church structure moved back to its new site to allow for the widening of Queens Boulevard. Note that the steeple has been removed.

View 1: May, 1923
Views 2,3: August, 1924
View 4: May, 1929

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
